1. Loading the data¶

The US Census dataset has 40 features, most of them categorical. Let us load the csv file into a pandas DataFrame to ease analysis and visualization.

2. Preliminary analysis¶

2.1 Missing values¶

Before analyzing the data, we must clean it. The missing values in the dataset are marked by ' ?' and not by the default nan. Hence to identify the proportion of missing data for each column, we must find the occurences of ' ?'.

We can see here that the four features concerning migration have 50% of missing values in the training set. For our analysis we will not consider those features.

The other features have a negligeable amount of missing values with respect to the overall number of samples, so we can choose to drop the corresponding rows.

2.2 Class balance¶

In [69]:
plt.figure(figsize=(15,6))
sns.countplot(x = cleaned_data['class']);

We can see that the classes in our data are highly imbalanced. From the metadata file, we know that the test set presents the same ratio. This will be a problem when constructing our predictive model. We would need to perform some transformations in the dataset to reduce this skew, such as oversampling of minority class and/or undersampling the majority class. Moreover, we would need to adapt our metrics since the predictive accuracy will not be informative (a classifier that outputs predicts only class 0 will have 95% accuracy with our test set).

For convenience, we are going to replace the class labels by -1 and 1.

In [70]:
# Let us change those class labels into 0 and 1
def change_label(cl):
    if cl==' - 50000.':
        cl = -1
    else:
        cl = 1
    return int(cl)
labels_train = cleaned_data['class'].map(change_label)
cleaned_data = pd.concat([cleaned_data.drop('class',axis=1),\
                          pd.DataFrame(labels_train, columns=['class'])],axis=1)

labels_test = data_test['class'].map(change_label)
data_test = pd.concat([data_test.drop('class',axis=1),\
                       pd.DataFrame(labels_test, columns=['class'])],axis=1)

2.3 Univariate statistics: continuous variables¶

Continuous variables are #0, #5, #16, #17, #18, #29, #38. As we said before, we will need to examine each one of them to judge their relevance, keeping in mind that our goal is to predict an income. Let us first look at the distribution of ages.

In [71]:

['age', 'wage per hour', 'capital gains', 'capital losses', 'dividends from stocks', 'num persons worked for employer', 'weeks worked in year']

print('%.2f %% of samples are children' %(cleaned_data[cleaned_data['age']<16].count()[1]/n_csamples*100))

25.60 % of samples are children

We can see here that 'age' is an informative feature on different levels. Unsurprisingly children (<18) are not present in class 1. In fact people in the high income class have mostly an age between 30 and 60. There are several possibilities of treatment for this feature: we can keep it as it is, or transform it into a new feature with a lower cardinality by regrouping some portions of ages. We will try the different cases and see how it impacts the predictions of our classifier.

The following four features concern the financial situation of a person. We will represent those with a scatter plot to visualize at which levels the different classes are concentrated.

How can we interpret the value of 0 for this feature? There can be various reasons: we can be talking about a child, a retiree. Since it is a numerical feature it is possible that some of the 0 represent an unknown value.

In fact more than 90% of our dataset has wage per hour of 0. Let us look at the remaining entries.

c) Capital gains, capital losses, dividends from stocks¶

Capital gains and losses are complementary information.

In [80]:
print(cleaned_data[cleaned_data['capital gains']>0]['capital losses'].value_counts())
print(cleaned_data[cleaned_data['capital losses']>0]['capital gains'].value_counts())

0    6938
Name: capital losses, dtype: int64
0    3696
Name: capital gains, dtype: int64

The two features are mutually exclusive. One who has gains has no losses and vice versa. Thus we can construct a new feature, allowing negative values for losses. By substracting the loss column to the gain column, we will simplify the data by reducing the number of features by 1, without losing any information.

In [81]:
cap_column = pd.DataFrame(cleaned_data['capital gains'] - cleaned_data['capital losses'],

cleaned_data = pd.concat([cleaned_data, cap_column], axis=1)

2.3 Univariate statistics: nominal variables¶

An interesting fact to notice is that we have a lot of categorical features, and most of them do not concern every person in our dataset. This is denoted by the instance 'Not in universe': an obvious example, if we have a child, he/she will probably not be concerned by the feature 'member of a labor union'.

# Define a function to get a bar plot on the population concerned by a given feature

def get_stats(feature):
    s = dict(cleaned_data[feature].value_counts())
    t = False
    
    # Extract proportion of not in universe
    if feature=='major industry code':
        if ' Not in universe or children' in s.keys():
            t = True
            p = s[' Not in universe or children'] / n_csamples * 100
            nu_stats = \
            cleaned_data[cleaned_data[feature]==' Not in universe or children']['class'].value_counts()
            tmp = cleaned_data[cleaned_data[feature]!=' Not in universe or children']
        else: 
            tmp = cleaned_data
            
    elif feature=='live in this house 1 year ago':
        if ' Not in universe under 1 year old' in s.keys():
            t = True
            p = s[' Not in universe under 1 year old'] / n_csamples * 100
            tmp = cleaned_data[cleaned_data[feature]!=' Not in universe under 1 year old']
            nu_stats = \
            cleaned_data[cleaned_data[feature]==' Not in universe under 1 year old']['class'].value_counts()
        else: 
            tmp = cleaned_data
            
    else:
        if ' Not in universe' in s.keys():
            t = True
            p = s[' Not in universe'] / n_csamples * 100
            nu_stats = \
            cleaned_data[cleaned_data[feature]==' Not in universe']['class'].value_counts()
            tmp = cleaned_data[cleaned_data[feature]!=' Not in universe']
        else:
            tmp = cleaned_data
    
    
    # Plot distribution of remaining instances
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,6))
    if t:
        plt.title('%s, concerns %.2f %% of total samples (the rest not in universe)' %(feature, 100 - p))
    else: 
        plt.title('%s' %(feature))
    sns.countplot(y=tmp[feature], hue=tmp['class'], order =\
             tmp[feature].value_counts().index)
    plt.show()
    
    # Print information about classes in the not in universe category
    if t:
        s = dict(nu_stats)
        s_total = dict(cleaned_data['class'].value_counts())
        s[-1] = s[-1]/s_total[-1]*100
        s[1] = s[1]/s_total[1]*100
        print('Ratio of classes for not in universe')
        print('Class -1: %.2f %% of total representatives not in universe for this feature' %(s[-1]))
        print('Class 1: %.2f %% of total representatives not in universe for this feature' %(s[1]))
        print('-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------')
    pass

As above, 'class of worker' seems to be an interesting feature for caracterizing our minority class, in the sense that most of them are concerned by this feature whereas 50% of the class -1 representatives are not.

Afterwards, we can see that 'member of labor union' and 'reason for unemployment' concern really a very small portion of both our instances, so we will not keep them as features to feed in our model.

Class 1 seems to be caracterized by 'Children or Armed Forces' and 'Full-Time schedulers' values for the 'full time employment stat. However this two values concern the majority of instances of class -1, so it may not be beneficial to keep this feature.

Finally most of the instances have a value of 0 for 'own business or self employed' feature. It does not seem to be discriminative since the great majority in each distinct values are instances of class -1. We will not keep this feature.

3. Feature extraction¶

To summarize the overall analysis, we need to write a function which will transform the train / test data frames into feature data frames, which afterwards could be treated by our model.

For the continuous variables, we can keep them as they are or transform them. As we have seen during our analysis, for some of those features, there are value areas which represent more one class than another (e.g. age < 18 is clearly class -1) and value areas which are 'neutral' (we seem to have both classes importantly present). Thus an idea to explore is to transform our features into ternary (sometimes binary) valued ones.

In [156]:
def get_features(data):
    
    # After testing, the classifiers perform better when 
    # the continuous variables are not transformed
    s00 = data['age'].map(lambda x: -1 if x<20 else 1) # child or not feature
    
    s0 = data['age']#.map(lambda x:\
                    #     -1 if x < 30 else 1 if 30<=x<70 else 0)
    s1 = data['wage per hour']#.map(lambda x:\
                    #     -1 if (x<1000) else 1)
    s2 = data['capital gain/loss']#.map(lambda x:\
                    #     -1 if (x < 500) else 1)
    s3 = data['dividends from stocks']#.map(lambda x:\
                    #     -1 if (x<100) else 1)
    s4 = data['num persons worked for employer']#.map(lambda x:\
                    #     -1 if x==0 else 0)
    s5 = data['weeks worked in year']#.map(lambda x:\
                    #     -1 if x < 27 else 1 if x==52 else 0)
    
    d1 = pd.get_dummies(data['major occupation code'])
    d2 = pd.get_dummies(data['major industry code'])
    
    l = [' Not in universe', ' Without pay', ' Never worked']
    s6 = data['class of worker'].map(lambda x: -1 if x in l else 0)
    
    s7 = data['race'].map(lambda x: -1 if x!=' White' else 1)
    s8 = data['sex'].map(lambda x:-1 if x!=' Male' else 1)
    s9 = data['citizenship'].map(lambda x: -1 if x!=' Native- Born in the United States' else 0)
    
    l = [' Bachelors degree(BA AB BS)', '  Masters degree(MA MS MEng MEd MSW MBA)',\
         ' Doctorate degree(PhD EdD)', '  Prof school degree (MD DDS DVM LLB JD)']
    s10 = data['education'].map(lambda x: -1 if x not in l else 0)
    s11 = data['tax filer status'].map(lambda x: -1 if x==' Nonfiler' else 0)
    
    l = [' Householder', ' Spouse of householder', ' Nonrelative of householder' ]
    s11 = data['detailed household summary in household'].map(lambda x: -1 if x not in l else 0)
    
    d3 = pd.get_dummies(data['marital status'])
    df = pd.concat([s00, s0, s1, s2, s3, s4, s5, s6, s7, s8, s9, s10, s11, d1, d2, d3], axis=1)
    return df

4. Predictive models¶

We will test and tweak several models for our prediction task. Since we transformed most of our features into binary yes or no, it seems natural to apply a decision tree model. We will use scikit-learns Random Forest classifier. In addition we will try using a Logistic Regression model and an SVM with a non linear kernel.

The class imbalance becomes a problem when building our predictive models. If we look at the accuracy of our predictor, it may be very good, but that does not mean that our model performs well. Let's illustrate this with an example. Let's consider just the 'age' feature, without modifications, and feed it into a Random Forest Classifier.

In [157]:
X_train = pd.concat([cleaned_data['age']], axis=1)
y_train = np.array(cleaned_data['class'])
X_test = pd.concat([data_test['age']], axis=1)
y_test = np.array(data_test['class'])

clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=10)
clf = clf.fit(X_train, y_train)

scores = cross_val_score(clf, X_train , y_train)
print(scores.mean())

y_pred = clf.predict(X_test)
cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
print('Confusion matrix: \n', cm)

0.938827986936
Confusion matrix: 
 [[93576     0]
 [ 6186     0]]

We obtain a predictive accuracy of 93,9% on the test set. This is misleading, as we can see on the confusion matrix, none of the instances from class 1 were correctly predicted, in fact no entry was attributed to class 1. Thus we must pay attention, and use other metrics than just the accuracy percentage to evaluate the quality of our model.

To evaluate the quality of our model we need to look at the ratio of true positive/negatives and false positive/negatives. Our use case has no particular sensitivity about the preference between ture positives and true negatives, unlike a clinical case where prediction errors one class can be more acceptable than on the other. Thus we would like an optimal precision on both classes.

Confusion matrix is a good visual indicator since we can see how well our model is performing in terms of precision and recall. Another tool that puts an emphasis on these metrics is the ROC curve, and the AUC metric.

SKLEARN DEFINITION: By definition a confusion matrix $C$ is such that $C_{i, j}$ is equal to the number of observations known to be in group i but predicted to be in group j. Thus in binary classification, the count of true negatives is $C_{0,0}$, false negatives is $C_{1,0}$, true positives is $C_{1,1}$ and false positives is $C_{0,1}$

In [158]:

plt.show()
print('AUC = ', auc(fpr, tpr))
print('F1 score = ', f1_score(y_test, y_pred))

  'precision', 'predicted', average, warn_for)

This is the ROC curve of the worst classifier we can get, it allows us to see what the predictive accuracy alone would not let us see, which is the real performance of our classifier when we have an imabalanced dataset. No F1 score can be extracted since no instance was classified as class 1.

4.1 Undersampling the majority class¶

Even if does not seem the best thing to do, we can heavily undersample the majority class to obtain a balanced dataset. The drawback is that we will end up with roughly 10-15% of the original dataset.

In [159]:
s = cleaned_data['class'].value_counts()
n = dict(s)[1]

s0 = cleaned_data[cleaned_data['class']==-1]
ss = s0.sample(n)
s1 = cleaned_data[cleaned_data['class']==1]

X_reduced = pd.concat([ss, s1])
#Shuffle once again
X_reduced = X_reduced.sample(frac=1.)

X_train_red = get_features(X_reduced)
y_train_red = X_reduced['class']

X_test = get_features(data_test)
y_test = data_test['class']

4.2 Oversampling the minority class¶

Another radical strategy could be completely oversampling the minority class to raise its number of samples to the number of representatives in the majority class. This augments the size of our dataset condsiderably, thus the computational complexity. We will try to use the SMOTE algorithm from the imbalanced-learn API (http://contrib.scikit-learn.org/imbalanced-learn/stable/api.html).

In [166]:
from imblearn.over_sampling import SMOTE
from collections import Counter

Oversampling the minority class with the SMOTE algorithm worsens considerably the results of the Random Forest Classifier. We have an AUC inferior to what we have obtained before but a higher F1 score. This is because we have much less error on predictions for class -1, however the errors on the other class have considerably risen.

Conclusion¶

The best model we got so far was the Random Forest Classifier trained on the reduced data set. For future improvement, the feature design should be studied more thoroughly since many possibilities were not explored in this notebook:

     - Study the performance of the model by adding or removing some features
     - Study the performance of the model by simplifying or not some features
     - Explore more thoroughly the correlation between all the different features
     - Try other over sampling / under sampling methods (the imblearn library provides different methods that would be interesting to test, different oversampling methods and also some combined over/under sampling methods)
     - Since the resulting feature matrix is sparse, we could try  some dimensionality reduction techniques such as PCA or TSVD
